<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-11-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-11-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="53" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d53">
                    <head>No. 53.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Carlisle</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-11-30"><hi rend="italic">November</hi> 30,
                            1888</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 27.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 44 of October 22
                        last, in which you report the final suppression of the military mutiny at
                        Sucre and the complete restoration of civil order.</p>
                    <p>The Department receives this information with satisfaction, and confidently
                        hopes that the restoration of domestic peace will prove auspicious of an era
                        of prosperity and advancement for Bolivia under the benign influence of a
                        stable constitutional government.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                            Bayard.</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                </div>
            </body></text></TEI>